What does this program print to `std::cout` when input is `5`? (Ignore `std::cerr` output.)

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int process(int n)
{
    std::cerr << "[process] n=" << n << "\n";
    int r = n * 3;
    std::cerr << "[process] r=" << r << "\n";
    return r;
}

int main()
{
    int x;
    std::cin >> x;
    std::cout << process(x) - 2 << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

The program should print the entry message before calling `work`, but no `[main] calling work` message appears in cerr output when run. What is the bug?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int work(int n)
{
    std::cerr << "[work] n=" << n << "\n";
    return n + 1;
}

int main()
{
    int x;
    std::cin >> x;
    int r = work(x);
    std::cerr << "[main] calling work" << "\n";
    std::cout << r << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

What does this program print to `std::cout` when input is `8`?

```cpp
